oncepts only. A model struct must not know about database storage, HTTP serialization, or any external framework.\n26. - They are the single shared vocabulary between handlers and repository/service interfaces. All interface method signatures must use these types.\n27. - When a domain concept requires different shapes at the DB or HTTP layer, create a separate DB model or viewmodel and add a mapping function. Do not add tags or fields to the business model to accommodate those layers.\n28. \n29. ---\n30. \n31. ## 3. Interfaces\n32. \n33. - All interfaces live in `business-logic/interfaces/`. They must be pure Go interfaces with no imports from `infrastructure/` or `web/`.\n34. - Define one interface per logical concern (e.g., `UrlRepository`, `UserRepository`, `ClickWriter`, `ShortcodeGenerator`).\n35. - Interface methods must only accept and return types from `business-logic/models/`, standard library types (`context.Context`, `error`, primitives), or other interface types. They must never reference Bun model structs, Huma types, or viewmodels.\n36. - Keep interfaces narrow: prefer several small interfaces over one large one.\n37. \n38. ---\n39. \n40. ## 4. Handlers\n41. \n42. - Handlers in `business-logic/handlers/` are **pure Go service structs** — they apply business logic, orchestrate repository and service calls, and return business models or errors. They have no knowledge of HTTP, Huma, Gin, or any web framework.\n43. - Handlers receive their dependencies (repository interfaces, service interfaces) by constructor injection — **never** by global variables or `init()`:\n44. \n45.   ```go\n46.   type UrlHandler struct {\n47.       urls    interfaces.UrlRepository\n48.       clicks  interfaces.ClickWriter\n49.   }\n50. \n51.   func NewUrlHandler(urls interfaces.UrlRepository, clicks interfaces.ClickWriter) *UrlHandler {\n52.       return &UrlHandler{urls: urls, clicks: clicks}\n53.   }\n54.   ```\n55. \n56. - Return standard Go `error` values. Declare **sentinel errors** or typed error structs in `business-logic/` for predictable domain failures (e.g., `ErrNotFound`, `ErrExpired`, `ErrConflict`, `ErrValidation`). The web layer is responsible for translating these into HTTP responses.\n57. - All domain-level validation (URL format, shortcode rules, SSRF checks, expiration) must be performed in the handler or in a dedicated validation helper within `business-logic/`.\n58. - Every log entry must include `user_id` (when authenticated) and all relevant entity IDs. Never log JWT tokens, OAuth secrets, or any sensitive user data.\n59. \n60. ---\n61. \n62. ## 5. URL Shortening Logic\n63. \n64. ### 5.1 Shortcode Generation\n65. \n66. - Shortcodes are generated using **Base62 encoding** (`[0-9A-Za-z]`, exactly 6 characters).\n67. - If a user supplies a custom shortcode it must be validated: alphanumeric + hyphens only, exactly 6 characters, checked against a reserved-words blocklist. Return `ErrValidation` on failure.\n68. - On shortcode collision (auto-generated), retry generation up to a reasonable limit; if all retries fail, return a wrapped error and log the event.\n69. - Shortcode generation must be encapsulated behind an interface in `business-logic/interfaces/` so it can be mocked in tests.\n70. \n71. ### 5.2 Long URL Validation\n72. \n73. Every long URL submitted by a user must be validated before storing:\n74. \n75. 1. Scheme must be `http` or `https`. Return `ErrValidation` otherwise.\n76. 2. Host must not be `localhost`, `127.0.0.1`, `::1`, or any loopback address.\n77. 3. Host must not resolve to an RFC-1918 private IP range (`10.x.x.x`, `172.16–31.x.x`, `192.168.x.x`) — SSRF prevention.\n78. 4. URL length must not exceed 2048 characters.\n79. \n80. Report any exception requests to this rule to the user before implementing them.\n81. \n82. ### 5.3 Expiration\n83. \n84. - `expires_at` is optional. When set, the handler must check it and return `ErrExpired` for expired links. The web layer maps `ErrExpired` to `410 Gone`.\n85. - Do not silently process expired links. Log the expiration event at `INFO` level.\n86. \n87. ---\n88. \n89. ## 6. Dependency Injection & Wiring\n90. \n91. - All interface implementations are wired at application startup (`main.go` or a dedicated `wire.go`). No handler or business logic code constructs its own concrete dependencies.\n92. - Use constructor functions for every handler and service, accepting their interface dependencies as parameters.\n93. - Do not use global variables to hold repository or service instances. Pass them through constructors.\n94. \n95. ---\n96. \n97. ## 7. Testing\n98. \n99. - Minimum **95% code coverage** for all packages under `business-logic/`.\n100. - Generate mock implementations with `mockgen` for all interfaces in `business-logic/interfaces/`. Place generated mocks in a `mocks/` sub-package alongside the interfaces (e.g., `business-logic/interfaces/mocks/`).\n101. - Handler tests must use these mocks — never real repository implementations.\n102. - Tests follow the **Arrange / Act / Assert** pattern.\n103. - Test files live alongside the code they test (e.g., `business-logic/handlers/url_handler_test.go`).\n104. - `main()` and auto-generated mock files are excluded from the 95% coverage requirement.\n105. \n106. ---\n107. \n108. ## 8. What Agents Must Not Do\n109. \n110. - Do not import any third-party package (Huma, Gin, Bun, etc.) from `business-logic/`. The only permitted imports are the Go standard library and other `business-logic/` packages.\n111. - Do not import `infrastructure/pg` (or any sub-package) from `business-logic/`. Always wire through interfaces.\n112. - Do not add ORM tags (`bun:\"...\"`) or HTTP tags (`json:\"...\"`, `validate:\"...\"`) to business model structs.\n113. - Do not return HTTP status codes or HTTP-specific error types from handlers; return sentinel or typed errors and let the web layer handle translation.\n114. - Do not process expired links silently — always return `ErrExpired` and log the event.\n115. - Do not construct concrete infrastructure dependencies inside handlers or business logic; always inject via interfaces.\n116. "}}

